00:25:15,060 --> 00:25:16,400
he could see in the sky.

566
00:25:17,240 --> 00:25:17,740
Again,

567
00:25:17,740 --> 00:25:19,920
pretty much just from the size of it.

568
00:25:19,960 --> 00:25:21,560
There are much more sophisticated ways

569
00:25:22,540 --> 00:25:27,120
of measuring distance than just by size and brightness.

570
00:25:28,160 --> 00:25:30,760
But that's clearly one way to measure the distance.

571
00:25:31,260 --> 00:25:32,620
And on the vertical axis,

572
00:25:32,780 --> 00:25:36,520
he measured the velocity of the galaxies.

573
00:25:36,860 --> 00:25:37,300
Well,

574
00:25:37,300 --> 00:25:37,840
first of all,

575
00:25:37,840 --> 00:25:38,960
the first thing he discovered

576
00:25:38,960 --> 00:25:42,000
is that all of the distant galaxies...

577
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:42,300
Now,

578
00:25:42,300 --> 00:25:43,480
distant to Hubble

579
00:25:44,500 --> 00:25:47,940
doesn't mean what we would call distant galaxies today.

580
00:25:48,620 --> 00:25:49,180
Hubble...

581
00:25:49,180 --> 00:25:49,660
When was Hubble?

582
00:25:49,800 --> 00:25:51,840
When did Hubble do these wonderful things?

583
00:25:52,120 --> 00:25:53,020
In the 20s sometime.

584
00:25:54,080 --> 00:25:54,640
Uh...

585
00:25:55,900 --> 00:25:57,020
Not 1820,

586
00:25:57,020 --> 00:25:57,440
1920.

587
00:25:58,000 --> 00:25:58,860
Did he really use galaxies,

588
00:25:58,860 --> 00:26:00,040
or did he use something else?

589
00:26:00,300 --> 00:26:01,180
He used galaxies.

590
00:26:01,180 --> 00:26:01,900
Yeah.

591
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:02,380
Oh,

592
00:26:02,380 --> 00:26:04,100
it's an interesting historical fact

593
00:26:04,100 --> 00:26:07,320
that up until...

594
00:26:07,320 --> 00:26:07,720
Let's see,

595
00:26:07,720 --> 00:26:08,320
when was it?

596
00:26:08,320 --> 00:26:09,280
I'm not exactly sure.

597
00:26:09,360 --> 00:26:09,440
Again,

598
00:26:09,440 --> 00:26:09,900
it was Hubble.

599
00:26:10,060 --> 00:26:12,520
Probably 1920 or something.

600
00:26:14,520 --> 00:26:15,620
I'm not sure when exactly.

601
00:26:16,280 --> 00:26:18,500
The idea of a galaxy didn't exist.

602
00:26:19,900 --> 00:26:23,500
All we knew about was one bunch of stars,

603
00:26:23,620 --> 00:26:24,400
the Milky Way,

604
00:26:24,400 --> 00:26:25,500
across the sky,

605
00:26:25,760 --> 00:26:28,140
and people spoke of an island universe,

606
00:26:28,500 --> 00:26:30,740
that we lived in an island of stars

607
00:26:30,740 --> 00:26:32,540
with nothing out further than that.

608
00:26:32,840 --> 00:26:35,230
They did discover that there

609
00:26:35,230 --> 00:26:37,620
were these blotchy things out there.

610
00:26:37,620 --> 00:26:40,760
But it was not recognized that those blotchy things

611
00:26:40,760 --> 00:26:42,800
were other island universes,

612
00:26:42,800 --> 00:26:43,580
so to speak.

613
00:26:43,780 --> 00:26:47,300
It wasn't really until sometime in the...

614
00:26:48,780 --> 00:26:52,000
in the middle of the early 20th century

615
00:26:53,439 --> 00:26:57,820
that Hubble realized that what he was seeing

616
00:26:57,820 --> 00:26:59,800
when he saw these smudges in the sky

617
00:26:59,800 --> 00:27:02,100
were collections of stars.

618
00:27:02,520 --> 00:27:05,220
That they were collections of huge numbers of stars

619
00:27:05,220 --> 00:27:07,600
which rivaled in size and in size

620
00:27:07,620 --> 00:27:09,660
and number of stars the Milky Way itself.

621
00:27:10,240 --> 00:27:12,400
So that was the first discovery.

622
00:27:12,620 --> 00:27:14,260
The universe is filled with galaxies.

623
00:27:14,900 --> 00:27:16,920
And then he,

624
00:27:16,920 --> 00:27:17,620
as I said,

625
00:27:17,620 --> 00:27:20,080
measured the distance of galaxies

626
00:27:20,620 --> 00:27:22,300
and the velocity of galaxies.

627
00:27:23,880 --> 00:27:24,960
And he discovered,

628
00:27:24,960 --> 00:27:27,140
first thing that surprised him,

629
00:27:27,840 --> 00:27:30,060
the galaxies are moving away from us.

630
00:27:30,860 --> 00:27:32,990
Apart from one or two galaxies

631
00:27:32,990 --> 00:27:35,120
which are very close to us,

632
00:27:35,220 --> 00:27:36,960
our closest neighbor,

633
00:27:36,960 --> 00:27:37,520
in fact,

634
00:27:37,620 --> 00:27:39,680
just happens to be moving toward us.

635
00:27:40,080 --> 00:27:42,300
It's a more or less accidental fact

636
00:27:42,300 --> 00:27:43,450
that it's so close to

637
00:27:43,450 --> 00:27:44,600
us that it's sort of trapped

638
00:27:44,600 --> 00:27:46,580
by our galaxy's gravity.

639
00:27:47,160 --> 00:27:50,040
And it happens to be moving toward us.

640
00:27:50,300 --> 00:27:51,800
What's the name of the closest galaxy?

641
00:27:52,200 --> 00:27:53,140
The Andromeda.

642
00:27:53,140 --> 00:27:54,080
Right.

643
00:27:54,220 --> 00:27:57,340
So the Andromeda is moving toward us.

644
00:27:58,840 --> 00:28:02,200
That is more or less an exception.

645
00:28:02,620 --> 00:28:05,040
If you look out beyond the Andromeda galaxy

646
00:28:05,040 --> 00:28:06,960
to galaxies three,

647
00:28:06,960 --> 00:28:08,400
four,

648
00:28:08,400 --> 00:28:08,720
five,

649
00:28:08,720 --> 00:28:09,920
six times further away

650
00:28:09,920 --> 00:28:11,260
or a hundred times further away,

651
00:28:11,260 --> 00:28:12,320
they're moving away.

652
00:28:12,780 --> 00:28:14,480
So that was the first discovery.

653
00:28:15,060 --> 00:28:16,700
Almost all the galaxies,

654
00:28:16,700 --> 00:28:17,460
and in particular,

655
00:28:17,480 --> 00:28:21,300
all of the distant galaxies were moving away from us.

656
00:28:21,840 --> 00:28:22,440
Furthermore,

657
00:28:22,440 --> 00:28:24,200
they were moving away from us

658
00:28:24,820 --> 00:28:28,180
by a velocity which depended on their distance.

659
00:28:28,600 --> 00:28:29,940
And when he plotted it,

660
00:28:31,180 --> 00:28:32,860
he got a perfect,

661
00:28:32,860 --> 00:28:33,400
exact,

662
00:28:33,400 --> 00:28:34,360
straight line.

663
00:28:35,340 --> 00:28:35,820
Nonsense.

664
00:28:35,820 --> 00:28:37,060
Of course he didn't get it.

665
00:28:37,160 --> 00:28:38,580
He got a mishmash

666
00:28:39,220 --> 00:28:41,640
which was all over the place.

667
00:28:45,260 --> 00:28:45,980
Error bars.

668
00:28:46,640 --> 00:28:48,480
But somehow he looked at this,

669
00:28:48,600 --> 00:28:50,800
and whether he was intuiting the right answer

670
00:28:50,800 --> 00:28:53,240
or he was a master of statistics,

671
00:28:53,480 --> 00:28:54,760
which I don't think he was,

672
00:28:54,900 --> 00:28:55,760
or whatever it was,

673
00:28:55,980 --> 00:28:58,740
he drew a straight line to it

674
00:28:58,740 --> 00:28:59,460
and he said,

675
00:28:59,460 --> 00:28:59,820
look,

676
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:03,060
velocity is proportional to distance.

677
00:29:03,540 --> 00:29:04,980
He actually didn't

678
00:29:05,040 --> 00:29:05,540
know why.

679
00:29:05,540 --> 00:29:06,560
He had no idea.

680
00:29:06,780 --> 00:29:08,720
The simple argument did not exist.

681
00:29:09,400 --> 00:29:12,260
It's been explained in an even simpler way

682
00:29:14,100 --> 00:29:15,180
than this,

683
00:29:15,180 --> 00:29:17,840
but this picture here

684
00:29:17,840 --> 00:29:22,220
is correct and really at the heart of the matter.

685
00:29:22,640 --> 00:29:25,740
But it was explained by other people just saying,

686
00:29:25,820 --> 00:29:25,920
look,

687
00:29:25,920 --> 00:29:27,380
why are you surprised

688
00:29:28,010 --> 00:29:30,960
that the fastest horse goes the furthest in a race?

689
00:29:31,160 --> 00:29:33,280
That if you look at a horse race,

690
00:29:33,480 --> 00:29:35,020
expect that the fastest horse

691
00:29:35,040 --> 00:29:36,320
is the fastest one that's gone the furthest.

692
00:29:37,580 --> 00:29:40,180
The fastest galaxy is most likely to be

693
00:29:40,180 --> 00:29:42,300
the one that's gotten furthest away from you.

694
00:29:42,600 --> 00:29:43,700
But that,

695
00:29:43,700 --> 00:29:45,960
of course,

696
00:29:45,960 --> 00:29:47,260
is just a...

697
00:29:50,720 --> 00:29:51,460
It's true,

698
00:29:51,460 --> 00:29:53,760
but this is the right way to say it.

699
00:29:54,140 --> 00:29:55,620
This is the right way to say it.

700
00:29:55,840 --> 00:29:59,280
Velocity is proportional to Hubble constant times d.

701
00:29:59,620 --> 00:30:00,100
Now,

702
00:30:00,100 --> 00:30:02,360
Hubble was not very good at the time

703
00:30:02,360 --> 00:30:04,160
at measuring the distances to the galaxies.

704
00:30:04,160 --> 00:30:05,180
This wasn't his own fault.

705
00:30:05,260 --> 00:30:07,420
He just had crude tools at the time.

706
00:30:08,120 --> 00:30:11,060
And he measured the galaxies as being maybe

707
00:30:11,060 --> 00:30:12,200
ten times closer,

708
00:30:12,200 --> 00:30:12,820
I think,

709
00:30:12,820 --> 00:30:13,840
than they actually were.

710
00:30:14,600 --> 00:30:17,480
So his Hubble constant was off by a bit,

711
00:30:17,540 --> 00:30:18,720
like a factor of ten.

712
00:30:19,660 --> 00:30:21,020
That had implications.

713
00:30:21,720 --> 00:30:23,000
Let me explain why.

714
00:30:25,580 --> 00:30:27,560
The bigger the Hubble...

715
00:30:28,160 --> 00:30:28,700
That,

716
00:30:28,700 --> 00:30:29,020
of course,

717
00:30:29,020 --> 00:30:30,340
meant that the Hubble constant

718
00:30:30,340 --> 00:30:32,320
was too big...too big or too small.

719
00:30:36,020 --> 00:30:36,580
Wait,

720
00:30:36,580 --> 00:30:38,320
he measured...which way did he measure it?

721
00:30:39,120 --> 00:30:43,140
He measured the Hubble constant being too big,

722
00:30:43,340 --> 00:30:43,820
as I remember.

723
00:30:43,820 --> 00:30:44,320
Yeah.

724
00:30:44,920 --> 00:30:47,300
He measured the Hubble constant being too big

725
00:30:47,300 --> 00:30:48,540
by a factor of ten.

726
00:30:49,240 --> 00:30:49,800
Now,

727
00:30:49,800 --> 00:30:51,560
that meant that his estimate,

728
00:30:51,560 --> 00:30:52,280
for example,

729
00:30:52,280 --> 00:30:56,700
of this galaxy moving away was ten times too big.

730
00:30:57,440 --> 00:30:59,600
Not that the velocity...the velocity was correct,

731
00:30:59,760 --> 00:31:02,080
but the estimate of the Hubble constant itself

732
00:31:02,080 --> 00:31:04,140
was ten times too big.

733
00:31:04,160 --> 00:31:06,080
It took a while to correct it.

734
00:31:06,360 --> 00:31:08,260
We're going to interpret...we're going to discover

735
00:31:08,260 --> 00:31:10,580
another interpretation of the Hubble constant.

736
00:31:11,440 --> 00:31:14,000
It's basically one over the age of the universe.

737
00:31:14,480 --> 00:31:15,940
I will tell you why later,

738
00:31:15,940 --> 00:31:16,560
not right now.

739
00:31:17,180 --> 00:31:20,400
So he had misestimated the age of the universe

740
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:21,560
by a factor of ten.

741
00:31:23,040 --> 00:31:23,280
What's that?

742
00:31:23,540 --> 00:31:25,600
It's really hard to tell how far away...

743
00:31:25,600 --> 00:31:27,080
It's really hard to tell how far away...

744
00:31:27,080 --> 00:31:29,280
And the more sophisticated tools came into play,

745
00:31:29,840 --> 00:31:32,480
but he misestimated things by a factor of ten.

746
00:31:32,560 --> 00:31:33,540
But he corrected them later.

747
00:31:33,540 --> 00:31:34,820
He corrected them.

748
00:31:35,260 --> 00:31:36,320
In any case,

749
00:31:36,320 --> 00:31:37,440
that's the Hubble law.

750
00:31:37,760 --> 00:31:38,520
It's very,

751
00:31:38,520 --> 00:31:39,080
very central.

752
00:31:39,400 --> 00:31:40,860
I said we can also do

753
00:31:40,860 --> 00:31:42,320
the same thing with more dimensions.

754
00:31:42,500 --> 00:31:44,980
Let's take two dimensions instead of one dimension,

755
00:31:45,600 --> 00:31:46,740
just for simplicity,

756
00:31:46,740 --> 00:31:47,520
x and y,

757
00:31:47,800 --> 00:31:48,700
and again,

758
00:31:48,700 --> 00:31:49,600
make a grid.

759
00:31:50,640 --> 00:31:51,440
Of course,

760
00:31:51,440 --> 00:31:53,680
it's nonsense to say that the galaxies

761
00:31:53,680 --> 00:31:55,160
are at the corners of the grid,

762
00:31:55,160 --> 00:31:55,680
but...

763
00:31:58,080 --> 00:32:00,260
but that's an extreme idealization.

764
00:32:00,520 --> 00:32:03,280
But let's imagine galaxies at the corners of the grid.

765
00:32:03,540 --> 00:32:06,260
Then every galaxy is labeled with two names,

766
00:32:06,300 --> 00:32:08,320
a first name and a last name,

767
00:32:08,320 --> 00:32:09,600
x and y.

768
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:14,620
And x and y stick with the galaxy.

769
00:32:15,360 --> 00:32:18,300
x and y of a galaxy doesn't change with time.

770
00:32:18,480 --> 00:32:19,320
It just is...

771
00:32:19,320 --> 00:32:21,420
It's just a label that labels the galaxy.

772
00:32:21,900 --> 00:32:27,380
But the distance between neighbors is again called a

773
00:32:27,380 --> 00:32:30,740
in both directions.

774
00:32:30,980 --> 00:32:31,240
Ah,

775
00:32:31,240 --> 00:32:33,060
that brings up an interesting question.

776
00:32:33,640 --> 00:32:34,980
Why is it...

777
00:32:34,980 --> 00:32:35,460
Do we know?

778
00:32:35,540 --> 00:32:38,980
Do we know that the separation between galaxies

779
00:32:38,980 --> 00:32:40,780
in this grid model...

780
00:32:41,480 --> 00:32:42,460
We could ask,

781
00:32:42,460 --> 00:32:44,440
how do we know that the separation

782
00:32:44,440 --> 00:32:47,400
between galaxies along the x-axis is the same

783
00:32:47,400 --> 00:32:50,000
as the separation between galaxies along the y-axis?

784
00:32:50,200 --> 00:32:50,820
Do we know?

785
00:32:50,880 --> 00:32:51,920
What do we know about it?

786
00:32:53,120 --> 00:32:53,680
Well,

787
00:32:53,680 --> 00:32:59,480
supposing the galaxies were not equally spaced,

788
00:32:59,860 --> 00:33:01,360
or not that they were...

789
00:33:01,360 --> 00:33:02,220
They were equally spaced,

790
00:33:02,220 --> 00:33:05,400
but they were more crowded in the x-direction

791
00:33:05,400 --> 00:33:07,180
than they were in the y-direction.

792
00:33:12,740 --> 00:33:13,780
At the corners,

793
00:33:13,780 --> 00:33:14,380
like that.

794
00:33:15,780 --> 00:33:17,320
When we look down into...

795
00:33:17,320 --> 00:33:18,640
When we look out into the sky,

796
00:33:19,340 --> 00:33:23,760
we would discover that things are different along the y-axis

797
00:33:23,760 --> 00:33:25,760
than they are along the x-axis.

798
00:33:26,100 --> 00:33:27,970
We'd look out along the

799
00:33:27,970 --> 00:33:29,840
x-axis and see very crowded galaxies.

800
00:33:30,300 --> 00:33:32,000
We'd look along the y-axis,

801
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:33,360
and discover they were very,

802
00:33:33,360 --> 00:33:34,540
very separated.

803
00:33:35,780 --> 00:33:36,600
We don't.

804
00:33:37,260 --> 00:33:40,480
We see the same distribution of galaxies

805
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:43,880
pretty much in every direction in the sky.

806
00:33:44,500 --> 00:33:45,980
There's a principle involved.

807
00:33:46,300 --> 00:33:47,000
It's not a principle.

808
00:33:47,660 --> 00:33:50,320
It's actually just a name for that fact.

809
00:33:50,520 --> 00:33:53,740
It is called the isotropy of the universe.

810
00:33:53,840 --> 00:33:55,320
Two basic names.

811
00:33:55,980 --> 00:33:58,100
The homogeneity of the universe.

812
00:33:58,980 --> 00:34:01,740
That means everywhere is the same.

813
00:34:02,500 --> 00:34:03,040
Now,

814
00:34:03,040 --> 00:34:05,040
this is everywhere is the same,

815
00:34:05,140 --> 00:34:06,700
at least on a scale larger

816
00:34:06,700 --> 00:34:08,260
than the distance between these galaxies.

817
00:34:08,719 --> 00:34:10,920
Looked at on a bigger scale,

818
00:34:11,179 --> 00:34:12,739
we would say every place is

819
00:34:12,739 --> 00:34:14,300
the same as every other place.

820
00:34:14,980 --> 00:34:17,420
Everybody has a couple of neighbors around them,

821
00:34:17,420 --> 00:34:17,960
and that's all.

822
00:34:18,900 --> 00:34:21,460
And every place is the same as every other place.

823
00:34:22,159 --> 00:34:24,380
This here is also homogeneous.

824
00:34:25,400 --> 00:34:28,080
This place is the same as this place,

825
00:34:28,179 --> 00:34:30,699
or has the same properties as this place over here.

826
00:34:32,080 --> 00:34:33,880
This one is the same as this one.

827
00:34:34,780 --> 00:34:36,350
There's no sense in which

828
00:34:36,350 --> 00:34:37,920
this one over here is special.

829
00:34:38,159 --> 00:34:39,360
No different than that one.

830
00:34:39,480 --> 00:34:40,639
No different than that one.

831
00:34:42,659 --> 00:34:45,820
But there is something different about this than this.

832
00:34:47,080 --> 00:34:49,300
It has to do with angles

833
00:34:49,300 --> 00:34:51,520
in the sky rather than positions.

834
00:34:53,780 --> 00:34:55,179
It's not isotropic.

835
00:34:55,440 --> 00:34:57,240
It isn't the same in every direction.

836
00:34:57,760 --> 00:34:59,260
It's the same in every place,

837
00:34:59,300 --> 00:35:01,000
but it isn't the same in every direction.

838
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:02,560
There's a directionality to this,

839
00:35:02,560 --> 00:35:04,040
a directional bias.

840
00:35:04,900 --> 00:35:06,200
When we look in the sky,

841
00:35:06,520 --> 00:35:10,000
we don't see different things in different directions.

842
00:35:10,560 --> 00:35:11,260
Of course,

843
00:35:11,260 --> 00:35:12,280
that's not entirely true.

844
00:35:12,480 --> 00:35:12,740
I mean,

845
00:35:12,740 --> 00:35:14,120
when I look up,

846
00:35:14,120 --> 00:35:15,960
I see something different than when I look down.

847
00:35:17,460 --> 00:35:20,280
When I look on a scale of our galaxy,

848
00:35:20,520 --> 00:35:22,740
if I look into the plane of the galaxy,

849
00:35:22,740 --> 00:35:23,820
I see the Milky Way.

850
00:35:23,960 --> 00:35:25,740
